         <div type="translation"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:id="zoor0286.translation"
              corresp="#zoor0286.transcription">
            <p>... (son) of Kassisos, (the) bouleutes, who died, - having lived thirty years -
                    on the 9th of (the) month Apellaios. You, be of good cheer. (He died) have a
                    good name.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The inscription records the date as the 9th day of the month Apellaios, that is, November 25. It has been further dated to the end of the fourth century or the beginning of the fifth century CE on the strength of other factors. The tombstone is one of about 700 discovered in Byzantine Zoora. The majority of the Greek tombstones from this location have been identified as Christian. The rectangular tombstone is broken at the top and chipped all around, resulting in a loss of text. The inscribed face is smoothed only in the area of the text. The text is engraved. Traces of guide-lines can be seen throughout the text, and remnants of a frame are also visable on the left and right. Lines 3, 6, and 9 as well as their associated guide-lines preserve red paint. The author suggests that Βουλα, mentioned in line 3, likely stands for Βολευτοῦ, a title given to municipal magistrates. She also notes that a variant of the name Kασσίσος is also attested elsewhere at Ghor es-Safi.</p>
         </div>
